'2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'UPDATE 1 p.m -- The White House has now clarified the timeline of the president\'s COVID-19 diagnosis. In a statement released to a number of national media outlets, Dr. Sean Conley, the president\'s doctor, said he "incorrectly" used the term 72 hours instead of "Day three." The president is said to have been diagnosed Thursday evening and received the experimental treatment of Regeneron on Friday. UPDATE 12:21 p.m -- In his first communication of the day, President Trump tweeted that he was "feeling well." The president expressed his gratitude to his care team at Walter Reed Medical Center. Doctors, Nurses and ALL at the GREAT Walter Reed Medical Center, and others from likewise incredible institutions who have joined them, are AMAZING!!!Tremendous progress has been made over the last 6 months in fighting this PLAGUE. With their help, I am feeling well! UPDATE 12:06 p.m. -- According to reports from the AP, a source familiar with the health of President Trump said the president did receive supplemental oxygen on Friday before being flown to Walter Reed. The question was sidestepped by the president\'s doctor, Dr. Sean Conley, at a news conference Saturday morning. UPDATE 11:49 a.m. -- More information continues to come off camera regarding Saturday morning\'s briefing of President Trump\'s health. A number of media outlets are reporting that an anonymous source told the Associated Press that the president\'s vital signs over the past 24 hours were "very concerning" but have have improved. That information was reportedly sent to a number of White House pool reporters. The unnamed person, who\'s familiar with the president\'s condition, says the next 48 hours are critical in terms of care. More updates are expected throughout the day. UPDATE: The president is said to be doing well while at Walter Reed Medical Center. He has reportedly been fever free for 24 hours. "The team and I are extremely happy with the progress he has made," White House physician, Dr. Sean Conley, said. Symptoms that President Trump had, like a cough and congestion, are said to be resolving. He is not on oxygen as of 10:42 a.m. Functions of his vital organs are said to be good with a saturation level of about 96%. Based off a line of questioning regarding if the president had been supplemental oxygen, it\'s not clear when or if he was. He will continue taking Remdesivir for the next 5-10 days after taking his first dose of the treatment of the last night. "It\'s hard to tell where he is on that course. Everyday we\'re evaluating if he needs to be here," Dr. Conley said, noting that the 7-10 day mark is critical in monitoring a possible inflammatory phase. However, there are some questions about the timeline of the president\'s diagnosis. President Trump\'s positive test result was announced early Friday morning, about 36 hours before Dr. Conley\'s update Saturday morning. In that update, it was said they were 72 hours into the diagnosis. White House Press Secretary Kayleigh McEnany saying Friday that when President Trump was "assured that he had tested positive for COVID-19, within an hour we put out that information to the American people." Dr. Conley wouldn\'t say when he would expect President Trump to be discharged. The president continues to work from presidential offices within Walter Reed. BETHESDA, Maryland (KWWL) -- White House physician, Dr. Sean Conley, will offer an update on the condition of President Donald Trump at 10 a.m. Trump tested positive yesterday for COVID-19 and went to Walter Reed Medical Center out of an abundance of caution. Watch the update on the KWWL Facebook here. This story will be updated following the update.
